Darshan, do you still see this issue?  Mugsie, recently fixed another issue that should have fixed this too - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/101954/'}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2014-07-15 22:04:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Vinod, Grahams patch fixed the problem on the API side, while leaving the door open for a common implementation on the RPC side.

With Grahams change, and another matching RPC change, we can avoid needing to list out all the exceptions in the decorator used here.

It's a tough one to explain how it would work though, it'll be easier to throw it together and submit for review."}, {'account_id': 12428, 'date': '2014-07-15 22:21:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hey,

The patch you linked fixes the API to log only when exception is not expected.  In this problem (in v1), we create a record by finding or creating a recordset first. If the prior throws an exception of RecordSetNotFound(), it's handled client side by calling later. (https://github.com/openstack/designate/blob/master/designate/api/v1/records.py#L42)

This client side exception handling cause some noise in the logs, which was opened as a bug by an operator. This is only in v1 and should not be an issue in v2 afais. Let me know if a patch is still needed and I will spend some cycles on it."}, {'account_id': 12428, 'date': '2014-07-15 22:23:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

^ What Kiall said, just read it.'}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2014-07-15 22:36:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

My (totally untested) port of Graham's API change to the RPC layer - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/107195/

In theory it should prevent all NotFound and Duplicate (+ any other expected exceptions) from being logged on either side of the RPC conversation."}, {'account_id': 8094, 'date': '2014-07-16 14:53:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Kiall, your change looks good.  The advantage being that we can now patch it at exception level rather than at function level.  The only reservation I have is overriding an internal messaging function - so we now need to keep track of changes to the affected functions in messaging.'}, {'account_id': 12428, 'date': '2014-07-23 22:07:46.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Was fixed by another commit which changed the way RPC server is setup, by overloading the dispatcher to patch the expected exceptions.'}]

commit_message:
RecordSetNotFound over RPC

Avoid throwing a trace when finding a single RecordSet
over RPC. Does not affect any exception handling as
the RPC client will still see the original exception.
Bug: #1304152

Change-Id: Ibcfda0fdc437fc1089a2d595281a3b0bef29b7f4

commit_message:
X.509 SSL certificate authentication plugin

Add a plugin for X.509 SSL certification authentication. This is similar to
Kerberos auth plugin. It must be used in conjunction with Apache mod_ssl.

DocImpact
SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I695e8deeb89826717ec859461ab2339d8af20805

commit_message:
Add a missing title in the storewize spec

This spec was missing the
"Other end user impact" section from the template.
This was preventing tox from passing the py27 test.

commit_message:
Set path to config file in tempest

Fix critical bug in preparation for Tempest config generation:
when `TEMPEST_CONFIG_FILE` is not presented, variables `TEMPEST_CONFIG` and
`OS_TEST_PATH` are set wrong.

Change-Id: Ic3011e7268f9d7d989a29295a126b247ddc6df2c

commit_message:
Don't update neutron VIF if MAC is duplicated

Conductor Manager update_port() can be used to change the MAC address of
a Port. If the requested address already exists, a MACAlreadyExists
exception is raised and returned to the client. This patch changes two
aspects of that method:

* If a MACAlreadyExists exception is raised, it does not need to be
  logged by the conductor. This patch adds it to the list of expected
  exceptions to pass back over RPC.
* If the MAC is associated to a VIF in neutron, do not update that VIF
  if the new MAC duplicates another MAC already known to Ironic.

Change-Id: Ie5ff082c4656e81c268f93cd51d75799087fe0c9

commit_message:
Add a hp1 region configs.

These are internal to the deploy infrastructure, but we've discussed its
details in IRC already... may as well make it easy for admins to share
and evolve.

Change-Id: I864830950a6f3bab04b10cbe00dd539ea6f3fd5a

commit_message:
Fixed dhcp & gateway ip conflict in PLUMgrid plugin

   * Adjust dhcp IP if conflicts with gateway IP
   * Added unit test case

Closes-Bug:1333442
Change-Id: Iaa4e63faf28b783e6b5dbc50035ca50ccde9951a

commit_message:
Don't expose X-Auth-Token in ceilometer CLI

Ceilometer CLI exposes X-Auth-Token in debug mode. This patch
replaces X-Auth-Token's value with '{SHA1}<sha1oftoken>'. Some
credentials are exposed by keystoneclient as ceilometerclient
uses keystoneclient to authenticate, it will be fixed in bug:
100414.

Change-Id: Ia6364314e4b4d26301f974582c0c2ba34b054c86
Partial-Bug: #1327019

commit_message:
Store volume backed snapshot in current tenant.

Fix owner of a creating volume backed snapshot.

Snapshot of an instance booted on a volume based on another tenant's
public image is created in the wrong tenant when invoked by admin.

Snapshot metadata (including owner) is based on image metadata. But
when the snapshot is being created by admin, Glance doesn't change
it's owner if it's set. So we forcibly remove owner (tenant)
attribute from image metadata.

Change-Id: I662dfa4f81e24cb2553ffa2578f4c8530eee9fd3
Closes-Bug: #1322195

commit_message:
Really ensure that sphinx <1.2 is installed

Because sphinx have release on pypi version suffixed by a letter for beta
purpose, ie: 1.2b3, even <1.2 is in requirement.txt 1.2b3 is installed.

This changes force the upper version to 1.1.999, to not install beta version
of sphinx 1.2.

Conflicts:
	global-requirements.txt

Change-Id: I951951ce24388cc1c7a9e472daf58a1e12124aba
Closes-bug: #1346827
(cherry picked from commit d79fb647a9800214caaa8679cf4030aa500c9f7a)

commit_message:
Removed use of BaseException.message from oslo.db

The usage of the .message attribute has been deprecated since Python 2.6.
However, the exceptions raised by SQLAlchemy can differ when using
unicode() and accessing .message. Using args[0] as a message is the best
we can do until SQLAlchemy is fully Python 3 compliant. SQLAlchemy itself
uses args[0] as a message internally.

Change-Id: I3b0edaba0604fa9885c145719287f236d7ba3fda
Closes-Bug: #1280435

commit_message:
Split ExtraConfig into compute + control

This allows specialisation of passthrough config between roles.

ExtraConfig has been left so that this patch can merge before the Heat changes
do. The next patch in this series removes ExtraConfig.

Change-Id: Ia90a62f4782b4c796578f098b6896e92715033ab

commit_message:
Add a Tunnel end-point variable for Neutron configuration

The HOST_IP address is being used as IP address
for end-point tunnel configruation. A new variable is
needed to specify a different IP address for the tunnel
end-point that Neutron will use

Change-Id: Ic7fb4853df167e78bf882af6a712b903db754dc2
Closes-bug: #1340433

[{'created': '2014-05-30 00:24:00.000000000', 'message': 'Removed use of BaseException.message from oslo.db

The usage of the .message attribute has been deprecated since Python 2.6.
However, the exceptions raised by SQLAlchemy can differ when using
unicode() and accessing .message. Using args[0] as a message is the best
we can do until SQLAlchemy is fully Python 3 compliant. SQLAlchemy itself
uses args[0] as a message internally.

Change-Id: I1b98811c129e8fbd2a4f0c578473292d2c2d9717
Closes-Bug: #1280435
'}]
commit_message:
Removed use of BaseException.message from oslo.db

The usage of the .message attribute has been deprecated since Python 2.6.
However, the exceptions raised by SQLAlchemy can differ when using
unicode() and accessing .message. Using args[0] as a message is the best
we can do until SQLAlchemy is fully Python 3 compliant. SQLAlchemy itself
uses args[0] as a message internally.

Change-Id: I1b98811c129e8fbd2a4f0c578473292d2c2d9717
Closes-Bug: #1280435

commit_message:
Big Switch: Remove consistency hash on full sync

Clears the consistency hash before performing a full
backend synchronization. Since all of the data is being
replaced, there is no reason to include this and it
currently requires special-casing to handle.

Closes-Bug: #1328233
Change-Id: Iace766d869dc78b041d3a5464e728b872c8347c2

commit_message:
NSX: Remove unneed call to _ensure_default_security_group

This patch removes an unneeded call to _ensure_default_security_group
which does not need to be called in create_security_group_rule_bulk()
as one would need to call get_security_groups() to look up the uuid
of the default security group which be would created it for us, BOOM!

Change-Id: I628a94c7ea9553dcefa68fa956f25244f0abbb18
Closes-bug: 1340536
(cherry picked from commit e2dac9daf39d9b519df14441bbeb99c3c4a7bfaa)

commit_message:
Remove RST online editor as rst.ninjs.org is down

http://rst.ninjs.org URL is pointing to a domain name troller
possibly due to a miss in domain renewal.
Based on no good alternatives, it's OK to remove it and just
specify where to find the generated file.

Change-Id: I44a5c59b68fa08183b375b8b642c0e1fb389adaa

commit_message:
NSX: fix router ports port_security_enabled=False

Previously there was a bug that resulted in a security group being
added to router ports which was not supported in NSX. Removing the
security group didn't actually completely solve the problem as we
never cleared the allowed_address_pairs on the router port. This
patch fixes this issue by disabling port_security_enabled on the
router port.

Change-Id: Ib61756e3bd5866318cbc3bb9856344571399d656
Closes-bug: 1344266
Related-bug: 1329043
(cherry picked from commit 25f1439ff356f78ab0d28a74dfc75d50e2f030b6)

In general, I don't think this is the appropriate way to tackle this problem, and I've yet to see a use case that is not more easily solved using resource multipliers (instance type families). I am totally agreed with encapsulating the resource reporting in an object. Resource manager should be open for extension, but closed for modification, see SOLID principles.

It just doesn't read or feel quite right in its current form... but I am struggling to put my finger on why though, and for that I apologise.

I think if you delete the existing vcpu reporting code, and make sure the extensible bits end up storing exactly the same thing in the database, and make the resource just to the minimal required to make vcpu work that way, lets see how that drives the code? I think that might be easier to grasp.

I kinda expected a single class that calculated the used resources for each instance, and added that into some state, then another method that writes out that state into the resources dict that gets persisted in the DB. Then a final method, that calls the extra from resource method, sees and diffs that vs the current stored state, and decides if the test passes. It just doesn't seem to read like that at the moment, but maybe I am just sleepy."}, {'account_id': 7461, 'date': '2014-05-13 15:03:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 25:

A resource plug-in is added to the resource tracker to allow
the types of resources allocated at the compute node to be
extensible. Information maintained by these plug-ins is written
to the extra_resources field of the compute_nodes table in the
database. The scheduler reads the extra_resources data and can
use information to determine scheduling decisions.

This is part of: blueprint extensible-resource-tracking

commit_message:
Add extensible resources to resource tracker

A resource plugin extension point is added to the resource
tracker to allow the types of resources allocated at the compute
node to be extensible. Information maintained by these plug-ins
is written to the compute_nodes table in the database. The
scheduler uses the information in the compute_nodes table to
determine scheduling decisions.

A plugin that implements vcpu resource tracking is included
and all other code for tracking vcpu has been removed. This
example ensures the plugins are tested in gate jobs.

Co-Authored-By: Andrea Rosa  <andrea.rosa@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Paul Murray  <pmurray@hp.com>
This is part of: blueprint extensible-resource-tracking

Change-Id: I64108338e3c958ba1276aaf113a68861cbe286f5

[{'created': '2014-07-23 15:57:02.000000000', 'message': 'Move server task start delete into check_delete_complete

Starting the task in handle_delete has the undesirable side-effect of
serializing the delete calls to nova, which results in a noticeable
serialization of the resource deletes for non-dependent resources.

Moving the start to check_delete_complete solves the problem, then the
resources all transition into DELETE_IN_PROGRESS at approximately the
same time, and it can be observed that the underlying nova servers are
set into deleting state in parallel.

Change-Id: Ie59f0903b7aba1e40737bece049dd4b0c6cda233
Partial-Bug: #1347775
'}]
commit_message:
Move server task start delete into check_delete_complete

Starting the task in handle_delete has the undesirable side-effect of
serializing the delete calls to nova, which results in a noticeable
serialization of the resource deletes for non-dependent resources.

Moving the start to check_delete_complete solves the problem, then the
resources all transition into DELETE_IN_PROGRESS at approximately the
same time, and it can be observed that the underlying nova servers are
set into deleting state in parallel.

Change-Id: Ie59f0903b7aba1e40737bece049dd4b0c6cda233
Partial-Bug: #1347775

commit_message:
Add RPC call to retrieve the parameters for a stack

Given a stack id, load the stack from the DB and return the
parameters and registry currently used.  These are from the
last stack-create or stack-update command and were combined
from the --parameters CLI and the environment file.

Partially-implements: blueprint troubleshooting-low-level-control
Closes-Bug: 1224828
Change-Id: Ie78dcde79518ac8598641c26366992e4ea4241f6

commit_message:
Test script for CRUD operations on trove instances

Adds a directory instances with test script 'test_instances.py' to
database api tests.
Adds related JSON supporting methods in client file
'instance_client.py' present in 'tempest/services/database/json'.
Adds api_schema for database instances in 'tempest/api_schema'
directory.
Addition of api_schema includes creation of a folder for database with
two files 'instances.py' and 'parameter_types.py'.
Modified 'tempest.conf.sample' and 'config.py' to add parameters
build_interval and build_timeout.
Modified 'base.py' of api database tests and clients.py to add the
details of instance_client.py.
Adds a method 'wait_for_db_instance_status' to waiters.py present in
'tempest/common' so as to implement logic to wait till db instance
reaches the desired status.

Change-Id: I0360dc4d7dc7eb8ac07498bca7289b93cf37c0f1

This represents a misunderstanding of the underlying mechanism.  Rename saml.py to mapped.py, and drop the 'method' mechanism.  But the method=Federation approach is wrong, redundant, and should not be implemented.

Using stevedore to load auth is a separate topic and can be addressed by its own BP."}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2014-07-09 22:32:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-2'}, {'account_id': 5956, 'date': '2014-07-10 10:26:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Adam, could you please elaborate on what you think is redundant and wrong about this approach as I can't see it.

Your suggestion of renaming saml2.py to mapped.py doesn't make any sense to me, as saml2.py calls a method which extracts attributes in a mod_shib/mod_mellon (saml2) specific way. If you could describe how your alternative works I would really appreciate it.

The main changes we would like to see are:

1. Determination of the user_id should be handled in a protocol specific way, rather than by the mapping layer. We want to see a user_id returned with the asserted attributes according to the protocol used.

2. There should be separation between the handling of protocol specific assertions and mapping. 
    a) Each protocol handling component should manage extraction of attributes / user_id.
    b) The resulting data should then be formatted uniformly so that mapping rules can be applied in a standardized way.

If you have an alternative way to achieve this I would love to hear it, or if you think that protocol handling and mapping should not be separable then I'd like to hear your reasons.

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2014-07-11 04:47:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

What we are going to do first is to rename the saml2.py to  mapping.py so that the various mapping based approaches can use common code.  If there needs to be something protocolo specific, they can use a subcalss, but that should be the exception, not the norm

the method name attribute of the current Saml2 adapter needs to be removed:  plugsin do not need to know their own "method name" as  the smae plugin can work for multiple "external" mapped protocols as you point out here, but the "method" needs to be selected by the client so that the client knows what to set up, as well as be specified by the config file for setting up the Auth controller.

The short is that you are right in saying this code should be reusable, but doing "method = federation" is wrong.'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2014-07-11 07:21:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi Adam

glad to see this is moving along nicely in the right direction.

However, you dont appear to have fully answered the point about the fact that the current code also handles the extraction of attributes from the environmental parameters in an Apache mod specific way (which is why you have the config parameter assertion_prefix=âMellonâ to remove prefixes when mod_mellon is used) This should not be part of the mapping module, but rather, part of the mod_mellon protocol specific handling module. Consider for example when two different protocols are being supported by Apache, say OpenID and SAML, and both format environmental parameters in different ways. The current hack wont work as you will need different parameters in keystone for the two different Apache modules. Thus there should be a separate protocol handling module (separate from the mapping module) in Keystone for each Apache module that formats the environmental parameters in different ways. This will also allow direct protocol handling to be done in Keystone when Apache mods dont exist (e.g. as is currently the case for ABFAB).

regards
David'}, {'account_id': 5956, 'date': '2014-07-11 08:09:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thanks for the clarification, it makes sense now.

One more question though, can we ensure that each protocol returns the user_id as well as the set of identity attributes?'}, {'account_id': 5956, 'date': '2014-07-16 12:49:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-16 12:49:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
generic-mapping-federation

Proposal to reengineer federation to ensure that the process for authentication
using a federated source is standardized for all protocols and that a user_id
is always returned with the extracted assertion data.

Change-Id: Iad52e40b80eb6b6fc7071b8ee1fe5b3d363da866

- gate-barbican-devstack-dsvm http://logs.openstack.org/02/108802/1/check/gate-barbican-devstack-dsvm/bbb08c2 : SUCCESS in 24m 24s'}, {'account_id': 9234, 'date': '2014-07-22 19:26:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I like the idea of RBAC first - then any other checks would only be done if the user has access to the resource in question.  Seems it would set a bad and potentially dangerous precedent to check things before we enforce RBAC.'}, {'account_id': 994, 'date': '2014-07-22 19:33:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

IMO RBAC check must be done after all the checks related to REST (content type/accept) is done. 

unauthorized response for bad content-type does not makes sense. 
I think we should get opinion from other members.'}, {'account_id': 1091, 'date': '2014-07-22 19:44:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

To me, its okay to make either check first as it will matter for error case only. In error case, having check which occurs more frequently might be good candidate but there is no way to establish that. 

Looking into code, content-type decorator looks into specific header only, not the payload which generally seen as cause for security concern.'}, {'account_id': 7262, 'date': '2014-07-23 15:22:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I really think we should always be doing auth checks first. See my comment on your launchpad bug.'}, {'account_id': 994, 'date': '2014-07-23 16:10:26.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

This is not needed'}]

commit_message:
Order execution of environment.d scripts

In case there are dependencies between scripts, IE one script defines an
env var another relies on.

This change should be in line with current expectations, given the
convention is to numerically prefix scripts in this directory.

Change-Id: Icc509f695d7a15a8026d8c7e463f06acf65499d7

For now, we'll document the current work-around on the wiki and revisit if the client work isn't done by the end of July."}, {'account_id': 9712, 'date': '2014-07-10 09:08:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Okay, thanks. While I see your point and I mostly agree, this doesn't match up with other OpenStack projects.

Examples:
Heat - https://github.com/openstack-dev/devstack/blob/master/lib/heat#L227-L231
Swift - https://github.com/openstack-dev/devstack/blob/master/lib/swift#L560-L564

Finally, looking at the registered endpoints on keystone all other services seem to include the version."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-22 21:25:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 7973, 'date': '2014-07-22 21:25:16.000000000', 'content': "Restored

Dougal,  Historically, the /vXXX was appended to the catalog entries, but we've had conversations with the Keystone team where they've said that appending the version to the catalog entry is a deprecated practice and that we should avoid it.

I think that in general we're trying to do things the right way, so we would prefer to keep the /v1 off the catalog which is why this change was abandoned, and a new blueprint was submitted https://review.openstack.org/#/c/108163/

Unfortunately, the reality is that we won't be able to get to this for at least another month, so John Wood and I agreed that it would be ok to merge this patch in now, and then remove it once the above blueprint is approved and implemented in both the API and the Client."}, {'account_id': 7973, 'date': '2014-07-22 21:25:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Update devstack endpoint creation to include v1

Currently with v1 missing, the barbican client doesn't include the /v1
part of the endpoint and gets 404's for all requests.

Change-Id: I14e6083084e4c05998dea2cacb5ac921c340d059

(1 comment)

a couple of concerns about this.

(a) as iccha says, please create a bug and that'll help understand what the problem is that you are attempting to address. I believe that a default linux/unix system comes with awk installed and everyone has access to it. So I'm not sure why running awk poses a challenge. Or maybe we're talking about a guest running on a non linux/unix system?

(b) the check added in parsing config file to handle a partial like comment runs the risk of getting into trouble if # is in a string. Say, if my password had the # character in it.

commit_message:
parse the mysql cnf file for password

This is a lighter way of getting the password rather than shelling out
to awk the file. This way the user the guestagent is running as does not
require access to awk.

Change-Id: Id8b74604099e6e941ea6e133d25fe4d44eed8e83

commit_message:
Exclude Routes 2.0

The py33 wheel published on PyPI for Routes is broken, and as a
result causes failures for our Py3k unit test jobs when it's a
project requirement. https://github.com/bbangert/routes/issues/31

Conflicts:
	global-requirements.txt

Change-Id: I66fe7a29362c45bc6af8b473f14433656e14d3d0
(cherry picked from commit 80366feb60fe3501c8c003efbd6905a1bc111b6e)

commit_message:
Add partial specs support in ML2 for multiprovider extension

ML2 provider network partial specs let admins choose some
multiprovider network attributes and let neutron choose remaining
attributes. This change provides the implementation for
multiprovider networks.

In practice, for VLAN/GRE/VXLAN segments provider:segmentation_id
choice can be delegated to neutron, in such case neutron try to find
a segment in tenant network pools which respects provided segment
attributes. For VLAN segments provider:physical_network choice can
also be delegated.

DocImpact

Implements blueprint provider-network-partial-specs

Change-Id: I1cf1441a179ec527674276b71e9924841f8570b6

commit_message:
Added trove config group section

The trove chapter in the user guide did not have
a section on how to use configuration groups.

This commit covers how to use config groups
to configure database parameters.

This commit completes the implementation of the
blueprint.

Edits for consistency - df

Change-Id: I749e7a1b0d2bfac799555844a15a99b24b46b7a2

commit_message:
Rename saml2_token_url to token_url

For the consisteny a property returning authentication url
should be called token_url.
This patch renames ``saml2_token_url`` to ``token_url`` in the
contrib.auth.v3.saml2.Saml2UnscopedPlugin plugin.

Change-Id: I435a118bb31338a37a29eec68b8e9ce50d163675

commit_message:
Enforce authenticated=False in saml2 plugin

All underlying HTTP calls executed via ``keystoneclient.session.Session``
object should have ``authenticated=False`` option enforced indicating the
plugin is not authenticated with the Identity Service yet.

Change-Id: I946f1ed6a55c4172d8f4bf6a24e5cbc3a00d1154

commit_message:
Add host argument to get_connect_string()

'localhost' value used to be hardcoded in get_connect_string().
Now it's possible to pass a custom host name as a function argument.
Wrote test for this

Change-Id: I3ae9f1a7df0bb378da1210cd89eef3e5f203cf34

commit_message:
Make MySQL regexes generic across MySQL drivers

Note that mysqlconnector raises InternalError whereas mysqldb raises
OperationalError when a deadlock is found.  The reported error codes and
messages are identical, however.

Change-Id: Iac9167e0777e0bf4361bcf6a8722923cce052b90

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-23 04:27:07.000000000', 'message': "Remove output filter on rabbitmq install

The original workaround was for an init script that grabbed stdout.
This was some time ago and I think it's safe to remove.

It can be a problem on Fedora; out-of-the-box some old F20 images can
have a broken dependency when rabbitmq installs.  With this in place,
all helpful output goes into the temp log file, but it is never shown
because the install_packages function exits the script.  Thus things
just stop and you have no idea why.

Change-Id: I2f5b934492a8c9d7b93e89fdcfa776bf15f25cb8
"}]
commit_message:
Remove output filter on rabbitmq install

The original workaround was for an init script that grabbed stdout.
This was some time ago and I think it's safe to remove.

It can be a problem on Fedora; out-of-the-box some old F20 images can
have a broken dependency when rabbitmq installs.  With this in place,
all helpful output goes into the temp log file, but it is never shown
because the install_packages function exits the script.  Thus things
just stop and you have no idea why.

Change-Id: I2f5b934492a8c9d7b93e89fdcfa776bf15f25cb8

commit_message:
notifier_strategy in glance-api.conf configurable in node attribute

set notifier_strategy in glance-api.conf.erb to
node['openstack']['mq']['image']['notifier_strategy']

commit_message:
Create file with all scenarios for use from CI

* Add scenarios from: Keystone, Nova, Glance, Cinder, Ceilometer, Heat
* Add scenarios for Authentication and Quotas
* All scenarios are configured with high levels of concurrency

Change-Id: Ic4f28c0187abda8a393900d85486df0628f375b6
